The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Sports | Briefs
                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                                           CRICKET BRIEFS
        Umpires, referees for Asia Cup announced  Calcutta: The International Cricket Council (ICC) on Thursday announced the names of umpires and referees to officiate in the Asia Cup to be held in Pakistan from June 24, says A Staff Reporter. Mike Procter of the Emirates Elite Panel of the ICC match referees will oversee the matches in Lahore while Alan Hurst, also of the elite panel, will supervise the matches to be played in Karachi, according to an ICC release.  Umpires  24 June: Bangladesh v UAE, Lahore (Simon Taufel, Ian Gould); Pakistan v Hong Kong, Karachi (Tony Hill, Brian Jerling) n 25 June: Bangladesh v Sri Lanka, Lahore (Simon Taufel, Ian Gould) n India v Hong Kong, Karachi (Tony Hill and Brian Jerling) n 26 June: Sri Lanka v UAE, Lahore (Simon Taufel, Ian Gould) n Pakistan v India, Karachi (Tony Hill, Brian Jerling)  
	Lawson rsquo;s view  Karachi: Pakistan coach Geoff Lawson on Thursday said the upcoming tri-series in Bangadesh would serve as an opportunity to assess the strengths and weaknesses of arch rivals India ahead of the Asia Cup. ldquo;India have shown in their recent performances that they have a very good one-day outfit and they are a strong opponent. The tri-series will allow us to judge the strengths and weaknesses of the Indian team for the Asia Cup which a very important tournament for all of us, rdquo; Lawson said. The former Aussie pacer also said the Bangladesh series would give his players a good practice. ldquo;This tri-series is a good curtain raiser and practice for the Asia Cup. rdquo;  
	Judge Warne  Mumbai: Australian spin legend Shane Warne will oversee the selection trials of the third season of a nationwide talent hunt, the winner of which would get a contract with the Rajasthan Royals in the 2010 IPL. lsquo;Cricket Star Twenty20 rsquo; was launched by Royals team owners Emerging Media on Thursday. The boys chosen through the hunt will be a part of the Cricket Star Academy and will also have the chance to interact, train and play with the Rajasthan Royals.   
	Akram advice  Mumbai: Young cricketers should realise that Twenty20 meet like the IPL are only for entertainment and should focus on the longer version of the game to develop themselves, former Pakistani fast bowler Wasim Akram said on Thursday. ldquo;In T20 there is no technique for the bowlers or batsmen. ldquo;A player rsquo;s skill is found in Tests, rdquo; Akram said.   
	MCC nod  London: Daniel Vettori and his teammates can slip into their smart trousers without the fear of incurring the wrath of the custodian of the game's law after the Marylebone Cricket Club (MCC) gave a thumbs-up to their 'micro-shine' pants. The MCC made it clear that the trousers, having a specially designed patch which aids shining the ball, don't breach the laws on laws artificial aides, which would definitely relieve Vettori and his teammates who gave it a try in the third and final Test against England on Thursday.
                                                                                                                                                               
